//       summary) via Modal.confirm. onSaved() fires once, after the modal is
//       closed, IF at least one row was actually updated.
//
// Effect per row { code, material_code }:
//   UPDATE product SET fk_main_fabric_code = material_code WHERE code = code
// via ctx.api.resource('product').update({ filter: { code }, values: {...} }).
// Classification before running anything:
//   - blank code or blank material_code            -> ignored entirely
//   - code not found in product                    -> a NEW product row is
//     created: { code, fk_main_fabric_code: material_code } (no confirmation
//     needed; if `product` has other required fields the create() call will
//     fail per-row and show up in the error list)
//   - current fk_main_fabric_code already matches   -> skipped as a no-op
//   - current fk_main_fabric_code is empty          -> updates automatically
//   - current fk_main_fabric_code differs (non-empty) -> conflict; shown in
//     its own table with checkboxes (unchecked by default) so the user
//     explicitly opts in per row before anything gets overwritten.
//
// Depends on: none.
//
// NOTE (2026-07): the product-table lookup converted from raw ctx.sql to
// ctx.api.resource().list() via a paginating fetchAllRows helper — ctx.sql.
// save() is admin/root-gated and silently fails for non-admin roles (see
// README §3). The lookup pulls the whole `product` table with no WHERE, so
// pagination matters here for the same reason as ui_import_product_material —
// a single .list() call would cap at pageSize and could miss codes on larger
// tables, silently breaking conflict/no-op detection. Do not revert to raw
// SQL or drop the pagination loop.
// =====================================================
const { useState } = React;
